```
@Component
public class MyWebClient {

    private final WebClient webClient;

    public MyWebClient(WebClient.Builder webClientBuilder) {
        this.webClient = webClientBuilder.build();
    }

    public Mono&lt;ServerHttpResponse&gt; getResponse() {
        return webClient.get()
                .uri(&quot;https://example.com&quot;)
                .exchangeToMono(response -&gt; {
                    if (response.statusCode().is2xxSuccessful()) {
                        Flux&lt;DataBuffer&gt; responseBody = response.body(BodyExtractors.toDataBuffers());
                        HttpHeaders headers = new HttpHeaders();
                        headers.addAll(response.headers().asHttpHeaders());
                        ServerHttpResponse serverHttpResponse = new ServerHttpResponseDecorator(new DefaultDataBufferFactory().wrap(responseBody));
                        serverHttpResponse.setStatusCode(response.statusCode());
                        serverHttpResponse.getHeaders().addAll(headers);
                        return Mono.just(serverHttpResponse);
                    } else {
                        return response.createException().flatMap(Mono::error);
                    }
                });
    }
}
```

in above example , The ```exchangeToMono() ``` method is used to convert the ```ClientResponse ``` returned by the WebClient to a Mono that emits a ```ServerHttpResponse```. Inside the lambda expression passed to ```exchangeToMono()```, the response object represents the ClientResponse returned by the WebClient.
you can use ```ServerWebExchange.getResponse()```  instead of ServerHttpResponse ,   both of theirs theory is same;

